work.p: This scrap of prose includes a line that would appear in a poem in the 1856 and 1860 editions of Leaves of Grass. The line, "Which is the poem or any book that is not diseased?" appeared in a slightly altered form in "Poem of Many in One" in 1856 and in Section 1 of "Chants Democratic and Native American" in 1860. Although the poem would remain in Leaves in various forms until the final edition, the line was dropped after 1860.

body.p: Of Health does not tell any more in the body, than it tells does in literature.—Which is the poem, or any book, that is not diseased?—(If perfect health appear in a poem, or any book, it surely propogatespropagates itself while many nations rise a great while.) Show perfect health and native qualities, and that which possesses them and you are welcome to all the rest.—
